'''Joseph Pedroza Diaz Jr.''' (born November 23, 1992) from [[South El Monte, California]] is an [[United States|American]] [[boxing|boxer]] who competed in the [[2012 Olympics]] as a [[bantamweight]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/team-usa/meet-the-team/news=boxing-u-s-men.html |accessdate=May 14, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515233338/http://www.nbcolympics.com/team-usa/meet-the-team/news%3Dboxing-u-s-men.html |archivedate=May 15, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and is the current NABF Featherweight Champion.<ref name="boxingscene1">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/joseph-diaz-jr-faces-hugo-partida-nabf-title--98554 |title=Joseph Diaz Jr. Faces Hugo Partida For NABF Title - Boxing News |website=Boxingscene.com |date=2015-11-24 |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Joseph is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] descent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corrales |first1=Danny |title=No Hablo Espanol with Boxer Joseph 'Jo Jo' Diaz |url=http://www.espn.com/video/clip?id=15054652 |website=ESPN |publisher=Espn.com |accessdate=2018-09-15}}</ref> He attended Kranz Intermediate at the age of 12-14. He is left-handed and fights [[southpaw]]. As a child he played baseball but took up boxing to learn self-defense. He is coached by his father.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kevin Baxter |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/07/sports/la-sp-oly-boxing-diaz-20120508 |title=Boxer Joseph Diaz Jr.'s biggest motivation is helping his family - latimes |website=Articles.latimes.com |date=2012-05-07 |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> He attended [[South El Monte High School]].

==Amateur career==
Prior to the Olympic Trials, Joseph was the two-time reigning national champion at bantamweight that included a win over [[Antonio Nieves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/joseph-diaz-jr-top-amateur-focuses-on-london--42111 |title=Joseph Diaz Jr. - Top Amateur Focuses on London - Boxing News |website=Boxingscene.com |date=2011-07-30 |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> Diaz became the first American boxer to qualify for the 2012 Olympics by becoming a quarter-finalist at the [[2011 World Amateur Boxing Championships]], where he defeated both [[2004 Olympics|2004 Olympic]] silver medalist [[Worapoj Petchkoom]] of [[Thailand]] and former world championship bronze medalist [[Óscar Valdez]] of [[Mexico]] but lost to [[Lázaro Álvarez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/diaz-becomes-first-american-qualify-london--44564 |title=Diaz Becomes First American to Qualify for London - Boxing News |website=Boxingscene.com |date=2011-10-04 |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> Díaz was the [[United States national amateur boxing featherweight champions|2011 U.S. National Champion at Featherweight]] at the U.S. Olympic Training Center in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/california-leaves-its-mark-on-olympic-trials--42365 |title=California Leaves Its Mark on The Olympic Trials - Boxing News |website=Boxingscene.com |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> Diaz fought in the [[2010-11 World Series of Boxing]]

At the [[Boxing at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's bantamweight#Top half|2012 Summer Olympics]] he beat [[Pavlo Ishchenko]], but ran into Alvarez in his second fight and lost again.

