{{Automatic taxobox | taxon = Liphistiidae | image = Ryuthela.tanikawai.female.-.tanikawa.jpg | image_caption = female ''[[Ryuthela tanikawai]]'' | image_upright = 1.15 | authority = [[Tord Tamerlan Teodor Thorell|Thorell]], 1869<ref name=WSC_gl50/> | diversity_link = List of Liphistiidae species | diversity = 8 genera, 96 species | diversity_ref = <ref name=WSC_stats>{{citation|title=Currently valid spider genera and species |work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/statistics |accessdate=2015-11-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103044611/http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/statistics/ |archivedate=2015-11-03 |df= }}</ref> | range_map = Distribution.liphistiidae.1.png | range_map_upright = 1.15 | subdivision_ranks = Genera | subdivision = See [[Liphistiidae#Genera|text.]] }}
The spider family '''Liphistiidae''', recognized by [[Tamerlan Thorell]] in 1869, comprises 8 [[genus|genera]] and about 100 [[species]] of medium-sized spiders from [[Southeast Asia]], [[China]], and [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Xu, X. |date=2015 |title=A genus-level taxonomic review of primitively segmented spiders (Mesothelae, Liphistiidae) |journal=ZooKeys |volume=488 |pp=121–151. |doi=10.3897/zookeys.488.8726 |display-authors=etal |pmid=25878527 |pmc=4389128}}</ref> They are among the most [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] living [[spider]]s, belonging to the suborder [[Mesothelae]]. In [[Japan]], the [[Kimura spider]] (''Heptathela kimurai'') is well known.
==Biology== [[Image:Heptathela.kimurai.yanbaruensis.burrow.-.tanikawa.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Burrow of ''[[Heptathela kimurai]]'']] Liphistiidae are tube-dwelling spiders that construct rudimentary trap-doors. They spend most of their time here and are rarely seen above ground. The medium to large spiders range from eight to twenty-three millimeters long. They are characterized by their downward pointing, daggerlike [[chelicerae]],<ref>{{cite journal| last=Haupt| first=J.| year=2004| title=The Mesothelae - a monograph of an exceptional group of spiders (Araneae: Mesothelae)| journal=Zoologica| volume=154| issue=8| ISSN=0044-5088| ISBN=3-510-55041-2}}</ref> and the segmented series of plates on the upper surface of the abdomen. The [[carapace]] is mostly flat, though it can be slightly elevated near the head. The eyes are distinctly clustered together on a single nodule. Anterior median eyes are small, but posterior median eyes are large and round. The lateral eyes are long and kidney-shaped. The distal leg segments have strong spines and three claws. Chelicerae are vertically attached to the cephalothorax.<ref name=Song>{{cite book| last1=Song| first1=D.X.| last2=Zhu| first2=M.S.| last3=Chen| first3=J.| year=1999| title=The Spiders of China| publisher=Hebei University of Science and Technology Publishing House, Shijazhuang}}</ref> In the past, they were frequently believed to lack venom, but in 2010 it was shown that at least ''[[Liphistius]]'' species have venom glands.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foelix |first1=R. |last2=Erb |first2=B. |date=2010 |title=Short communication: Mesothelae have venom glands |journal=The Journal of Arachnology |volume=38 |pp=596–598 |lastauthoramp=yes |doi=10.1636/b10-30.1}}</ref>
They are active at night and live for many years. Although most species live in burrows, cave-dwelling species also fasten their retreats to the cave walls. Both burrows and retreats are sealed with woven doors.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Murphy| first1=Frances| last2=Murphy| first2=John| year=2000| title=An Introduction to the Spiders of South East Asia| publisher=Malaysian Nature Society, Kuala Lumpur}}</ref> Trapdoor nests are generally built in shady areas with moss or sparse vegetation. Some make silk trip-lines radiating away from the burrow entrance. Adult males sometimes wander in search for females, but females rarely leave their burrows. The respiratory system consists only of [[book lungs]], which could help explain why they are relatively inactive.<ref name=CoddingtonLevy1991>{{cite journal| last1=Coddington| first1=J.A.| last2=Levi| first2=H.W.| year=1991| title=Systematics and Evolution of Spiders (Araneae)| journal=Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst.| volume=22| pages=565–592.| doi=10.1146/annurev.es.22.110191.003025}}</ref>
==Malaysian species== Three of the ''Liphistius'' species known to exist in Malaysia are endemic to only one or two caves.<ref>[http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com/photopage1.htm Caves of Malaysia]</ref> The most well known is ''[[Liphistius batuensis]]'', which is found in [[Batu Caves]]. Other species that can be found in Malaysia include ''[[Liphistius malayanus]]'', ''[[Liphistius murphyorum]]'' and ''[[Liphistius desultor]]''. The Malaysian trapdoor spiders are protected by local law, though continuous threats come from loss of habitat and collection by exotic pet traders. It is believed that these species are endemic and once an isolated habitat is destroyed, the species may go extinct.
==Systematics== Although they have downward pointing chelicerae like the [[Mygalomorphae]], there is no close relationship between the two. It is thought that the common ancestor of all spiders was orthognath and that in the [[Opisthothelae]], comprising Mygalomorphae (mostly tarantulas) and [[Araneomorphae]] (all other spiders), only the Araneomorphae changed their alignment of chelicerae, while the mygalomorphs retained this [[symplesiomorphic]] feature.<ref name=CoddingtonLevy1991/> [[Image:Ryuthela.sasakii.female.-.takinawa.jpg|thumb|250px|right|''[[Ryuthela|Ryuthela sasakii]]'']]
===Phylogeny=== [[Molecular phylogenetics|Molecular phylogenetic studies]] have repeatedly shown that the family is [[Monophyly|monophyletic]], at least as regards extant (living) species. The relationship between the genera is shown in the following cladogram:<ref name=XuLiuChenChen15>{{Cite journal |last1=Xu |first1=Xin |last2=Liu |first2=Fengxiang |last3=Cheng |first3=Ren-Chung |last4=Chen |first4=Jian |last5=Xu |first5=Xiang |last6=Zhang |first6=Zhisheng |last7=Ono |first7=Hirotsugu |last8=Pham |first8=Dinh Sac |last9=Norma-Rashid |first9=Y. |last10=Arnedo |first10=Miquel A. |last11=Kuntner |first11=Matjaž |last12=Li |first12=Daiqin |date=2015 |title=Extant primitively segmented spiders have recently diversified from an ancient lineage |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B |volume=282 |issue=1808 |page=20142486 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2014.2486 |pmid=25948684 |lastauthoramp=yes |pmc=4455790}}</ref>
{{barlabel |size=8 |at1=1|label1=Southeast Asia|bar1=green |at2=2.5|label2=Japan, Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands|bar2=purple |at3=6|label3=China, northern Vietnam|bar3=brown |cladogram= {{clade |style=line-height:100% |label1=Liphistiidae |1={{cladex |label1=Liphistiinae |1=''Liphistius''|barbegin1=green|barend1=green |label2=Heptathelinae |2={{cladex |1={{cladex |1=''Ryuthela''|barbegin1=purple |2=''Heptathela''|barend2=purple }} |2={{cladex |1=''Qiongthela''|barbegin1=brown |2={{cladex |1={{cladex |1=''Ganthela''|bar1=brown |2=''Sinothela''|bar2=brown }} |2={{cladex |1=''Vinathela''|bar1=brown |2=''Songthela''|barend2=brown }} }} }} }} }} }} }}
In 1923, [[Kyukichi Kishida]] suggested dividing the family into two subfamilies, Liphistiinae and Heptathelinae, corresponding to the genera ''Liphistius'' and ''Heptathela''.<ref name=Kish23>{{Cite journal |last1=Kishida |first1=K. |date=1923 |title=''Heptathela'', a new genus of liphistiid spiders |journal=Annotationes Zoologicae Japonenses |volume=10 |pages=235–242 }}</ref> More genera have since been added to the family, but the subfamily division has been upheld by modern phylogenetic studies. ''Liphistius'', the sole genus in the subfamily Liphistiinae, is found only in Southeast Asia (Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Malaysia and Sumatra). The Heptathelinae are found further north: five genera in northern Vietnam and China and two genera in Japan and offshore islands (Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands).<ref name=XuLiuChenChen15/>
===Genera=== {{As of|2015|11}}, the [[World Spider Catalog]] accepted the following [[extant taxon|extant]] genera:<ref name=WSC_gl50>{{cite web |title=Family: Liphistiidae Thorell, 1869 (genus list) | work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genlist/50 |accessdate=2015-11-10 }}</ref> *''[[Ganthela]]'' <small>Xu & Kuntner, 2015 </small> – China *''[[Heptathela]]'' <small>Kishida, 1923 </small> – Japan, Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands *''[[Liphistius]]'' <small>[[Jørgen Matthias Christian Schiødte|Schiødte]], 1849 </small> – Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Malaysia, Sumatra *''[[Qiongthela]]'' <small>Xu & Kuntner, 2015 </small> – China, Vietnam *''[[Ryuthela]]'' <small>Haupt, 1983 </small> – Okinawa, Ryukyu Islands *''[[Sinothela]]'' <small>Haupt, 2003 </small> – China *''[[Songthela]]'' <small>Ono, 2000 </small> – Vietnam, China *''[[Vinathela]]'' <small>Ono, 2000 </small> – Hong Kong, China, Vietnam
One genus of fossil spiders, ''[[Cretaceothele]]'' <small>Wunderlich, 2015</small>, was originally placed in this family,<ref name=Wund15>{{cite journal| last1=Wunderlich |first1=Jörg |date=2015 |title=On the evolution and classification of spiders, the Mesozoic spider faunas, and descriptions of new Cretaceous taxa mainly in amber from Myanmar (Burma) (Arachnida: Araneae) |journal=Beiträge zur Araneologie |volume=9 |pp=21–408 }}</ref> but it was subsequently transferred to the separate family [[Cretaceothelidae]].<ref>{{cite book |author =Jörg Wunderlich |year=2017 |chapter=New and rare fossil spiders (Araneae) in mid Cretaceous amber from Myanmar (Burma), including the description of new extinct families of the suborders Mesothelae and Opisthothelae as well as notes on the taxonomy, the evolution and the biogeography of the Mesothelae |editor=Jörg Wunderlich |title=Beiträge zur Araneologie, 10 |publisher= |volume= |pages=72–279 |isbn= }}</ref> {{clear}}
==Fossil record== While some [[Carboniferous]] fossil spiders have been assigned to [[Mesothelae]], the only fossil to be explicitly placed in the family Liphistiidae is ''Cretaceothele lata'' Wunderlich, 2015 from the Cretaceous Burmese amber of [[Myanmar]]. The fossil genus was diagnosed as having an eye-field wider than that in living species.<ref name=Wund15/>
